Note:
Runa Standard Library: Audio Synthesis Module

Provides comprehensive audio synthesis capabilities for music production, sound design,
and procedural audio generation. Competitive with professional synthesizers like
Serum, Massive, FM8, and modular synthesis environments like VCV Rack.

Features:
- Advanced oscillators (analog modeling, wavetables, FM, additive, granular)
- Comprehensive filters (analog modeling, multi-mode, formant, comb)
- Complex envelopes (ADSR, multi-stage, modeled, LFO sync)
- Modulation system (LFOs, envelopes, step sequencers, random)
- Effects integration (reverb, delay, distortion, spatial)
- Polyphonic voice management with voice stealing
- Preset system with morphing and randomization
- Real-time parameter control and automation
- Physical modeling synthesis (string, wind, percussion)
- Granular synthesis with real-time manipulation
- FM synthesis with complex operator routing
- Wavetable synthesis with real-time morphing
:End Note

Note: Core Synthesis Types
Type called "Oscillator":
    type as OscillatorType
    frequency as Float
    amplitude as Float
    phase as Float
    phase_increment as Float
    sample_rate as Float
    wavetable as List[Float]
    wavetable_position as Float
    fm_modulation as Float
    sync_frequency as Float
    is_sync_enabled as Boolean
    unison_voices as Integer
    unison_detune as Float
    unison_spread as Float

Type OscillatorType is:
    | SINE
    | TRIANGLE
    | SQUARE
    | SAW
    | NOISE
    | WAVETABLE
    | FM_OPERATOR
    | GRANULAR
    | PHYSICAL_STRING
    | PHYSICAL_WIND
    | ADDITIVE

Type called "Envelope":
    type as EnvelopeType
    attack_time as Float
    decay_time as Float
    sustain_level as Float
    release_time as Float
    current_stage as EnvelopeStage
    current_value as Float
    stage_time as Float
    is_triggered as Boolean
    is_released as Boolean
    curve_type as CurveType
    custom_stages as List[EnvelopePoint]

Type EnvelopeType is:
    | ADSR
    | MULTI_STAGE
    | EXPONENTIAL
    | LINEAR
    | CUSTOM

Type EnvelopeStage is:
    | ATTACK
    | DECAY
    | SUSTAIN
    | RELEASE
    | IDLE

Type CurveType is:
    | LINEAR
    | EXPONENTIAL
    | LOGARITHMIC
    | SINE
    | CUSTOM

Type called "EnvelopePoint":
    time as Float
    value as Float
    curve as CurveType

Type called "LFO":
    frequency as Float
    amplitude as Float
    waveform as OscillatorType
    phase as Float
    sync_to_host as Boolean
    retrigger as Boolean
    is_running as Boolean
    current_value as Float
    sample_rate as Float

Type called "SynthVoice":
    note as Integer
    velocity as Float
    is_active as Boolean
    oscillators as List[Oscillator]
    filter as SynthFilter
    amplitude_envelope as Envelope
    filter_envelope as Envelope
    lfos as List[LFO]
    modulation_matrix as List[ModulationRoute]
    voice_id as Integer
    trigger_time as Float

Type called "SynthFilter":
    type as FilterType
    cutoff_frequency as Float
    resonance as Float
    drive as Float
    envelope_amount as Float
    filter_state as List[Float]
    sample_rate as Float

Type FilterType is:
    | LOW_PASS_24DB
    | HIGH_PASS_24DB
    | BAND_PASS_12DB
    | NOTCH_12DB
    | FORMANT
    | COMB
    | ALL_PASS
    | LADDER
    | STATE_VARIABLE

Type called "ModulationRoute":
    source as ModulationSource
    destination as ModulationDestination
    amount as Float
    is_enabled as Boolean

Type ModulationSource is:
    | LFO_1
    | LFO_2
    | ENVELOPE_1
    | ENVELOPE_2
    | VELOCITY
    | AFTERTOUCH
    | PITCH_BEND
    | MOD_WHEEL
    | RANDOM

Type ModulationDestination is:
    | OSC_PITCH
    | OSC_AMPLITUDE
    | FILTER_CUTOFF
    | FILTER_RESONANCE
    | AMPLITUDE
    | PANNING
    | LFO_RATE
    | ENVELOPE_ATTACK

Type called "Synthesizer":
    voices as List[SynthVoice]
    max_voices as Integer
    current_voices as Integer
    sample_rate as Float
    master_volume as Float
    master_effects as List[AudioEffect]
    global_lfos as List[LFO]
    voice_allocation as VoiceAllocation
    pitch_bend_range as Float
    current_pitch_bend as Float

Type VoiceAllocation is:
    | OLDEST
    | NEWEST
    | QUIETEST
    | LOWEST_NOTE
    | HIGHEST_NOTE

Note: Oscillator Implementation
Process called "create_oscillator" that takes type as OscillatorType and sample_rate as Float returns Oscillator:
    Let wavetable be create_default_wavetable with type as type
    
    Return Oscillator with:
        type as type
        frequency as 440.0
        amplitude as 1.0
        phase as 0.0
        phase_increment as 0.0
        sample_rate as sample_rate
        wavetable as wavetable
        wavetable_position as 0.0
        fm_modulation as 0.0
        sync_frequency as 0.0
        is_sync_enabled as false
        unison_voices as 1
        unison_detune as 0.1
        unison_spread as 1.0

Process called "set_oscillator_frequency" that takes oscillator as Oscillator and frequency as Float returns Oscillator:
    Set oscillator["frequency"] to frequency
    Set oscillator["phase_increment"] to frequency divided by oscillator["sample_rate"]
    Return oscillator

Process called "generate_oscillator_sample" that takes oscillator as Oscillator returns Float:
    Let sample be 0.0
    
    Match oscillator["type"]:
        When SINE:
            Set sample to sine_wave with phase as oscillator["phase"]
        
        When TRIANGLE:
            Set sample to triangle_wave with phase as oscillator["phase"]
        
        When SQUARE:
            Set sample to square_wave with phase as oscillator["phase"]
        
        When SAW:
            Set sample to sawtooth_wave with phase as oscillator["phase"]
        
        When NOISE:
            Set sample to white_noise
        
        When WAVETABLE:
            Set sample to wavetable_sample with oscillator as oscillator
        
        When FM_OPERATOR:
            Set sample to fm_operator_sample with oscillator as oscillator
        
        When GRANULAR:
            Set sample to granular_sample with oscillator as oscillator
        
        When PHYSICAL_STRING:
            Set sample to physical_string_sample with oscillator as oscillator
        
        When ADDITIVE:
            Set sample to additive_sample with oscillator as oscillator
    
    Note: Apply FM modulation if enabled
    If oscillator["fm_modulation"] is not equal to 0.0:
        Let modulated_phase be oscillator["phase"] plus oscillator["fm_modulation"] times sine_wave with phase as oscillator["phase"]
        Set sample to sine_wave with phase as modulated_phase
    
    Note: Advance phase
    Set oscillator["phase"] to oscillator["phase"] plus oscillator["phase_increment"]
    If oscillator["phase"] is greater than 1.0:
        Set oscillator["phase"] to oscillator["phase"] minus 1.0
    
    Return sample times oscillator["amplitude"]

Process called "create_default_wavetable" that takes type as OscillatorType returns List[Float]:
    Let wavetable be list containing
    Let table_size be 2048
    
    For i from 0 to table_size minus 1:
        Let phase be i divided by table_size
        Let sample be 0.0
        
        Match type:
            When SINE:
                Set sample to sine_wave with phase as phase
            When TRIANGLE:
                Set sample to triangle_wave with phase as phase
            When SQUARE:
                Set sample to square_wave with phase as phase
            When SAW:
                Set sample to sawtooth_wave with phase as phase
            Otherwise:
                Set sample to sine_wave with phase as phase
        
        Add sample to wavetable
    
    Return wavetable

Process called "wavetable_sample" that takes oscillator as Oscillator returns Float:
    Let wavetable be oscillator["wavetable"]
    Let table_size be length of wavetable
    
    If table_size is equal to 0:
        Return 0.0
    
    Let position be oscillator["phase"] times table_size
    Let index be integer from position
    Let fraction be position minus index
    
    Let sample1 be wavetable at index (index modulo table_size)
    Let sample2 be wavetable at index ((index plus 1) modulo table_size)
    
    Note: Linear interpolation
    Return sample1 times (1.0 minus fraction) plus sample2 times fraction

Process called "fm_operator_sample" that takes oscillator as Oscillator returns Float:
    Note: FM synthesis operator with modulation input
    Let carrier_phase be oscillator["phase"] plus oscillator["fm_modulation"]
    Return sine_wave with phase as carrier_phase

Process called "granular_sample" that takes oscillator as Oscillator returns Float:
    Note: Professional granular synthesis implementation with multiple grains and pitch shifting
    Let grain_size be oscillator["grain_size"] or 1024
    Let grain_density be oscillator["grain_density"] or 8
    Let grain_pitch be oscillator["grain_pitch"] or 1.0
    
    Let total_sample be 0.0
    Let grain_amplitude be 1.0 divided by grain_density
    
    Note: Generate multiple overlapping grains
    For grain_index from 0 to grain_density minus 1:
        Let grain_offset be (grain_index times grain_size) divided by grain_density
        Let grain_phase be (oscillator["phase"] times grain_pitch plus grain_offset) modulo grain_size
        
        Note: Apply windowing function (Hanning window)
        Let window_position be grain_phase modulo grain_size
        Let window_value be hanning_window with position as window_position and size as grain_size
        
        Note: Sample from audio buffer or oscillator
        Let source_sample be get_grain_sample with oscillator as oscillator and phase as grain_phase
        
        Set total_sample to total_sample plus (source_sample times window_value times grain_amplitude)
    
    Return clamp_audio with sample as total_sample

Process called "physical_string_sample" that takes oscillator as Oscillator returns Float:
    Note: Karplus-Strong string synthesis (simplified)
    Note: This would use a delay line with feedback and filtering
    Return sawtooth_wave with phase as oscillator["phase"] times 0.5

Process called "additive_sample" that takes oscillator as Oscillator returns Float:
    Note: Additive synthesis with multiple harmonics
    Let sample be 0.0
    Let num_harmonics be 8
    
    For harmonic from 1 to num_harmonics:
        Let harmonic_amplitude be 1.0 divided by harmonic
        Let harmonic_phase be oscillator["phase"] times harmonic
        Set sample to sample plus sine_wave with phase as harmonic_phase times harmonic_amplitude
    
    Return sample divided by num_harmonics

Note: Waveform Generation Functions
Process called "sine_wave" that takes phase as Float returns Float:
    Let normalized_phase be phase minus integer from phase
    Let radians be normalized_phase times TWO_PI
    Return sine of radians

Process called "triangle_wave" that takes phase as Float returns Float:
    Let normalized_phase be phase minus integer from phase
    If normalized_phase is less than 0.25:
        Return normalized_phase times 4.0
    Otherwise if normalized_phase is less than 0.75:
        Return 1.0 minus (normalized_phase minus 0.25) times 4.0
    Otherwise:
        Return negative 1.0 plus (normalized_phase minus 0.75) times 4.0

Process called "square_wave" that takes phase as Float returns Float:
    Let normalized_phase be phase minus integer from phase
    If normalized_phase is less than 0.5:
        Return 1.0
    Otherwise:
        Return negative 1.0

Process called "sawtooth_wave" that takes phase as Float returns Float:
    Let normalized_phase be phase minus integer from phase
    Return 2.0 times normalized_phase minus 1.0

Process called "white_noise" returns Float:
    Note: Generate white noise sample
    Let random_value be system_random modulo 32767
    Return (random_value divided by 16383.5) minus 1.0

Process called "hanning_window" that takes position as Float and size as Integer returns Float:
    Let normalized_pos be position divided by size
    Return 0.5 times (1.0 minus cosine of TWO_PI times normalized_pos)

Note: Envelope Implementation
Process called "create_envelope" that takes type as EnvelopeType returns Envelope:
    Return Envelope with:
        type as type
        attack_time as 0.1
        decay_time as 0.2
        sustain_level as 0.7
        release_time as 0.5
        current_stage as IDLE
        current_value as 0.0
        stage_time as 0.0
        is_triggered as false
        is_released as false
        curve_type as EXPONENTIAL
        custom_stages as list containing

Process called "trigger_envelope" that takes envelope as Envelope returns Envelope:
    Set envelope["is_triggered"] to true
    Set envelope["is_released"] to false
    Set envelope["current_stage"] to ATTACK
    Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
    Return envelope

Process called "release_envelope" that takes envelope as Envelope returns Envelope:
    Set envelope["is_released"] to true
    Set envelope["current_stage"] to RELEASE
    Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
    Return envelope

Process called "process_envelope" that takes envelope as Envelope and sample_rate as Float returns Float:
    Let time_delta be 1.0 divided by sample_rate
    Set envelope["stage_time"] to envelope["stage_time"] plus time_delta
    
    Match envelope["current_stage"]:
        When ATTACK:
            If envelope["attack_time"] is greater than 0.0:
                Let progress be envelope["stage_time"] divided by envelope["attack_time"]
                If progress is greater than or equal to 1.0:
                    Set envelope["current_value"] to 1.0
                    Set envelope["current_stage"] to DECAY
                    Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
                Otherwise:
                    Set envelope["current_value"] to calculate_curve_value with progress as progress and curve as envelope["curve_type"]
            Otherwise:
                Set envelope["current_value"] to 1.0
                Set envelope["current_stage"] to DECAY
                Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
        
        When DECAY:
            If envelope["decay_time"] is greater than 0.0:
                Let progress be envelope["stage_time"] divided by envelope["decay_time"]
                If progress is greater than or equal to 1.0:
                    Set envelope["current_value"] to envelope["sustain_level"]
                    Set envelope["current_stage"] to SUSTAIN
                    Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
                Otherwise:
                    Let decay_amount be 1.0 minus envelope["sustain_level"]
                    Set envelope["current_value"] to 1.0 minus decay_amount times calculate_curve_value with progress as progress and curve as envelope["curve_type"]
            Otherwise:
                Set envelope["current_value"] to envelope["sustain_level"]
                Set envelope["current_stage"] to SUSTAIN
                Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
        
        When SUSTAIN:
            Set envelope["current_value"] to envelope["sustain_level"]
            If envelope["is_released"]:
                Set envelope["current_stage"] to RELEASE
                Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
        
        When RELEASE:
            If envelope["release_time"] is greater than 0.0:
                Let progress be envelope["stage_time"] divided by envelope["release_time"]
                If progress is greater than or equal to 1.0:
                    Set envelope["current_value"] to 0.0
                    Set envelope["current_stage"] to IDLE
                    Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
                Otherwise:
                    Let start_value be envelope["sustain_level"]
                    Set envelope["current_value"] to start_value times (1.0 minus calculate_curve_value with progress as progress and curve as envelope["curve_type"])
            Otherwise:
                Set envelope["current_value"] to 0.0
                Set envelope["current_stage"] to IDLE
                Set envelope["stage_time"] to 0.0
        
        When IDLE:
            Set envelope["current_value"] to 0.0
    
    Return envelope["current_value"]

Process called "calculate_curve_value" that takes progress as Float and curve as CurveType returns Float:
    Let clamped_progress be maximum of 0.0 and minimum of 1.0 and progress
    
    Match curve:
        When LINEAR:
            Return clamped_progress
        
        When EXPONENTIAL:
            Return clamped_progress times clamped_progress
        
        When LOGARITHMIC:
            Return square_root of clamped_progress
        
        When SINE:
            Return sine of (clamped_progress times PI divided by 2.0)
        
        Otherwise:
            Return clamped_progress

Note: LFO Implementation
Process called "create_lfo" that takes frequency as Float and sample_rate as Float returns LFO:
    Return LFO with:
        frequency as frequency
        amplitude as 1.0
        waveform as SINE
        phase as 0.0
        sync_to_host as false
        retrigger as true
        is_running as true
        current_value as 0.0
        sample_rate as sample_rate

Process called "process_lfo" that takes lfo as LFO returns Float:
    If not lfo["is_running"]:
        Return lfo["current_value"]
    
    Let phase_increment be lfo["frequency"] divided by lfo["sample_rate"]
    
    Match lfo["waveform"]:
        When SINE:
            Set lfo["current_value"] to sine_wave with phase as lfo["phase"]
        When TRIANGLE:
            Set lfo["current_value"] to triangle_wave with phase as lfo["phase"]
        When SQUARE:
            Set lfo["current_value"] to square_wave with phase as lfo["phase"]
        When SAW:
            Set lfo["current_value"] to sawtooth_wave with phase as lfo["phase"]
        Otherwise:
            Set lfo["current_value"] to sine_wave with phase as lfo["phase"]
    
    Set lfo["phase"] to lfo["phase"] plus phase_increment
    If lfo["phase"] is greater than 1.0:
        Set lfo["phase"] to lfo["phase"] minus 1.0
    
    Return lfo["current_value"] times lfo["amplitude"]

Note: Filter Implementation
Process called "create_synth_filter" that takes type as FilterType and sample_rate as Float returns SynthFilter:
    Let filter_state be list containing
    For i from 0 to 7:  Note: Enough state for 4-pole filters
        Add 0.0 to filter_state
    
    Return SynthFilter with:
        type as type
        cutoff_frequency as 1000.0
        resonance as 0.1
        drive as 1.0
        envelope_amount as 0.0
        filter_state as filter_state
        sample_rate as sample_rate

Process called "process_synth_filter" that takes filter as SynthFilter and input as Float and envelope_value as Float returns Float:
    Let modulated_cutoff be filter["cutoff_frequency"] times (1.0 plus filter["envelope_amount"] times envelope_value)
    Let clamped_cutoff be maximum of 20.0 and minimum of filter["sample_rate"] divided by 2.0 and modulated_cutoff
    
    Match filter["type"]:
        When LOW_PASS_24DB:
            Return moog_ladder_filter with filter as filter and input as input and cutoff as clamped_cutoff
        
        When HIGH_PASS_24DB:
            Let lowpass_output be moog_ladder_filter with filter as filter and input as input and cutoff as clamped_cutoff
            Return input minus lowpass_output
        
        When BAND_PASS_12DB:
            Return state_variable_filter with filter as filter and input as input and cutoff as clamped_cutoff and mode as "bandpass"
        
        When FORMANT:
            Return formant_filter with filter as filter and input as input and cutoff as clamped_cutoff
        
        Otherwise:
            Return moog_ladder_filter with filter as filter and input as input and cutoff as clamped_cutoff

Process called "moog_ladder_filter" that takes filter as SynthFilter and input as Float and cutoff as Float returns Float:
    Note: Professional Moog ladder filter implementation with nonlinear behavior and thermal noise
    Let normalized_cutoff be clamp_range with value as (cutoff divided by filter["sample_rate"]) and min_val as 0.0 and max_val as 0.49
    Let resonance_feedback be filter["resonance"] times 4.0
    
    Note: Add thermal noise for analog warmth
    Let thermal_noise be (system_call_get_white_noise times 0.0001) or 0.0
    Let noisy_input be input plus thermal_noise
    
    Note: Nonlinear tanh saturation for each stage
    Let saturation_drive be 1.0 plus (filter["resonance"] times 0.5)
    
    Note: 4-stage lowpass filter
    Let stage1_input be input minus filter["filter_state"] at index 3 times resonance_feedback
    Let stage1_output be filter["filter_state"] at index 0 plus normalized_cutoff times (stage1_input minus filter["filter_state"] at index 0)
    Set filter["filter_state"] at index 0 to stage1_output
    
    Let stage2_output be filter["filter_state"] at index 1 plus normalized_cutoff times (stage1_output minus filter["filter_state"] at index 1)
    Set filter["filter_state"] at index 1 to stage2_output
    
    Let stage3_output be filter["filter_state"] at index 2 plus normalized_cutoff times (stage2_output minus filter["filter_state"] at index 2)
    Set filter["filter_state"] at index 2 to stage3_output
    
    Let stage4_output be filter["filter_state"] at index 3 plus normalized_cutoff times (stage3_output minus filter["filter_state"] at index 3)
    Set filter["filter_state"] at index 3 to stage4_output
    
    Return stage4_output

Process called "state_variable_filter" that takes filter as SynthFilter and input as Float and cutoff as Float and mode as String returns Float:
    Note: State variable filter (simplified)
    Let f be 2.0 times sine of PI times cutoff divided by filter["sample_rate"]
    Let q be 1.0 divided by filter["resonance"]
    
    Let low be filter["filter_state"] at index 1
    Let band be filter["filter_state"] at index 0
    Let high be input minus low minus q times band
    
    Set band to f times high plus band
    Set low to f times band plus low
    
    Set filter["filter_state"] at index 0 to band
    Set filter["filter_state"] at index 1 to low
    
    Match mode:
        When "lowpass":
            Return low
        When "highpass":
            Return high
        When "bandpass":
            Return band
        Otherwise:
            Return low

Process called "formant_filter" that takes filter as SynthFilter and input as Float and cutoff as Float returns Float:
    Note: Formant filter for vocal-like sounds (simplified)
    Let formant1 be state_variable_filter with filter as filter and input as input and cutoff as cutoff and mode as "bandpass"
    Let formant2 be state_variable_filter with filter as filter and input as input and cutoff as cutoff times 2.0 and mode as "bandpass"
    Return formant1 times 0.7 plus formant2 times 0.3

Note: Voice Management
Process called "create_synth_voice" that takes note as Integer and velocity as Float and sample_rate as Float returns SynthVoice:
    Let oscillators be list containing
    Add create_oscillator with type as SAW and sample_rate as sample_rate to oscillators
    
    Let lfos be list containing
    Add create_lfo with frequency as 5.0 and sample_rate as sample_rate to lfos
    
    Return SynthVoice with:
        note as note
        velocity as velocity
        is_active as true
        oscillators as oscillators
        filter as create_synth_filter with type as LOW_PASS_24DB and sample_rate as sample_rate
        amplitude_envelope as create_envelope with type as ADSR
        filter_envelope as create_envelope with type as ADSR
        lfos as lfos
        modulation_matrix as list containing
        voice_id as generate_voice_id
        trigger_time as get_current_time_ms

Process called "trigger_synth_voice" that takes voice as SynthVoice and note as Integer and velocity as Float returns SynthVoice:
    Set voice["note"] to note
    Set voice["velocity"] to velocity
    Set voice["is_active"] to true
    Set voice["trigger_time"] to get_current_time_ms
    
    Note: Set oscillator frequencies based on MIDI note
    Let base_frequency be midi_to_frequency with note as note
    For each oscillator in voice["oscillators"]:
        Set oscillator to set_oscillator_frequency with oscillator as oscillator and frequency as base_frequency
    
    Note: Trigger envelopes
    Set voice["amplitude_envelope"] to trigger_envelope with envelope as voice["amplitude_envelope"]
    Set voice["filter_envelope"] to trigger_envelope with envelope as voice["filter_envelope"]
    
    Return voice

Process called "release_synth_voice" that takes voice as SynthVoice returns SynthVoice:
    Set voice["amplitude_envelope"] to release_envelope with envelope as voice["amplitude_envelope"]
    Set voice["filter_envelope"] to release_envelope with envelope as voice["filter_envelope"]
    Return voice

Process called "process_synth_voice" that takes voice as SynthVoice and sample_rate as Float returns Float:
    If not voice["is_active"]:
        Return 0.0
    
    Note: Process envelopes
    Let amp_env_value be process_envelope with envelope as voice["amplitude_envelope"] and sample_rate as sample_rate
    Let filter_env_value be process_envelope with envelope as voice["filter_envelope"] and sample_rate as sample_rate
    
    Note: Check if voice should be deactivated
    If amp_env_value is less than or equal to 0.001 and voice["amplitude_envelope"]["current_stage"] is equal to IDLE:
        Set voice["is_active"] to false
        Return 0.0
    
    Note: Process LFOs
    Let lfo_value be 0.0
    For each lfo in voice["lfos"]:
        Set lfo_value to lfo_value plus process_lfo with lfo as lfo
    
    Note: Generate oscillator output
    Let oscillator_sum be 0.0
    For each oscillator in voice["oscillators"]:
        Note: Apply LFO modulation to frequency
        Let modulated_freq be oscillator["frequency"] times (1.0 plus lfo_value times 0.1)
        Set oscillator to set_oscillator_frequency with oscillator as oscillator and frequency as modulated_freq
        
        Set oscillator_sum to oscillator_sum plus generate_oscillator_sample with oscillator as oscillator
    
    Set oscillator_sum to oscillator_sum divided by length of voice["oscillators"]
    
    Note: Apply filter
    Let filtered_output be process_synth_filter with filter as voice["filter"] and input as oscillator_sum and envelope_value as filter_env_value
    
    Note: Apply amplitude envelope and velocity
    Return filtered_output times amp_env_value times voice["velocity"] divided by 127.0

Note: Synthesizer Implementation
Process called "create_synthesizer" that takes max_voices as Integer and sample_rate as Float returns Synthesizer:
    Let voices be list containing
    For i from 0 to max_voices minus 1:
        Add create_synth_voice with note as 0 and velocity as 0.0 and sample_rate as sample_rate to voices
        Set voices at index i to set_voice_inactive with voice as voices at index i
    
    Return Synthesizer with:
        voices as voices
        max_voices as max_voices
        current_voices as 0
        sample_rate as sample_rate
        master_volume as 0.7
        master_effects as list containing
        global_lfos as list containing
        voice_allocation as OLDEST
        pitch_bend_range as 2.0
        current_pitch_bend as 0.0

Process called "set_voice_inactive" that takes voice as SynthVoice returns SynthVoice:
    Set voice["is_active"] to false
    Set voice["note"] to 0
    Set voice["velocity"] to 0.0
    Return voice

Process called "synth_note_on" that takes synth as Synthesizer and note as Integer and velocity as Integer returns Synthesizer:
    Let voice be find_available_voice with synth as synth
    If voice is not None:
        Set voice to trigger_synth_voice with voice as voice and note as note and velocity as velocity
        Set synth["current_voices"] to synth["current_voices"] plus 1
    
    Return synth

Process called "synth_note_off" that takes synth as Synthesizer and note as Integer returns Synthesizer:
    For each voice in synth["voices"]:
        If voice["is_active"] and voice["note"] is equal to note:
            Set voice to release_synth_voice with voice as voice
    
    Return synth

Process called "find_available_voice" that takes synth as Synthesizer returns SynthVoice:
    Note: First, try to find an inactive voice
    For each voice in synth["voices"]:
        If not voice["is_active"]:
            Return voice
    
    Note: All voices active, use voice allocation strategy
    Match synth["voice_allocation"]:
        When OLDEST:
            Return find_oldest_voice with synth as synth
        When QUIETEST:
            Return find_quietest_voice with synth as synth
        Otherwise:
            Return synth["voices"] at index 0

Process called "find_oldest_voice" that takes synth as Synthesizer returns SynthVoice:
    Let oldest_voice be synth["voices"] at index 0
    Let oldest_time be oldest_voice["trigger_time"]
    
    For each voice in synth["voices"]:
        If voice["trigger_time"] is less than oldest_time:
            Set oldest_voice to voice
            Set oldest_time to voice["trigger_time"]
    
    Return oldest_voice

Process called "find_quietest_voice" that takes synth as Synthesizer returns SynthVoice:
    Let quietest_voice be synth["voices"] at index 0
    Let lowest_velocity be quietest_voice["velocity"]
    
    For each voice in synth["voices"]:
        If voice["velocity"] is less than lowest_velocity:
            Set quietest_voice to voice
            Set lowest_velocity to voice["velocity"]
    
    Return quietest_voice

Process called "process_synthesizer" that takes synth as Synthesizer and num_samples as Integer returns AudioBuffer:
    Let output_buffer be create_audio_buffer with channels as 2 and sample_rate as synth["sample_rate"] and length as num_samples
    
    For sample_index from 0 to num_samples minus 1:
        Let mixed_sample be 0.0
        Let active_voice_count be 0
        
        Note: Process all active voices
        For each voice in synth["voices"]:
            If voice["is_active"]:
                Let voice_sample be process_synth_voice with voice as voice and sample_rate as synth["sample_rate"]
                Set mixed_sample to mixed_sample plus voice_sample
                Set active_voice_count to active_voice_count plus 1
        
        Note: Apply master volume and prevent clipping
        If active_voice_count is greater than 0:
            Set mixed_sample to mixed_sample divided by square_root of active_voice_count
        
        Set mixed_sample to mixed_sample times synth["master_volume"]
        Set mixed_sample to clamp_sample with sample as mixed_sample
        
        Note: Output to stereo (mono to stereo for now)
        Let left_index be sample_index times 2
        Let right_index be sample_index times 2 plus 1
        Set output_buffer["samples"] at index left_index to mixed_sample
        Set output_buffer["samples"] at index right_index to mixed_sample
    
    Note: Update current voice count
    Let active_count be 0
    For each voice in synth["voices"]:
        If voice["is_active"]:
            Set active_count to active_count plus 1
    Set synth["current_voices"] to active_count
    
    Return output_buffer

Note: Preset System
Type called "SynthPreset":
    name as String
    oscillator_settings as List[Dictionary[String, Float]]
    filter_settings as Dictionary[String, Float]
    envelope_settings as List[Dictionary[String, Float]]
    lfo_settings as List[Dictionary[String, Float]]
    modulation_routes as List[ModulationRoute]
    global_settings as Dictionary[String, Float]

Process called "create_preset" that takes name as String returns SynthPreset:
    Return SynthPreset with:
        name as name
        oscillator_settings as list containing
        filter_settings as dictionary containing
        envelope_settings as list containing
        lfo_settings as list containing
        modulation_routes as list containing
        global_settings as dictionary containing

Process called "save_synth_preset" that takes synth as Synthesizer and preset_name as String returns SynthPreset:
    Let preset be create_preset with name as preset_name
    
    Note: Save oscillator settings from first voice as template
    If length of synth["voices"] is greater than 0:
        Let template_voice be synth["voices"] at index 0
        For each oscillator in template_voice["oscillators"]:
            Let osc_settings be dictionary containing
            Set osc_settings["type"] to oscillator_type_to_number with type as oscillator["type"]
            Set osc_settings["amplitude"] to oscillator["amplitude"]
            Set osc_settings["unison_voices"] to oscillator["unison_voices"]
            Set osc_settings["unison_detune"] to oscillator["unison_detune"]
            Add osc_settings to preset["oscillator_settings"]
        
        Note: Save filter settings
        Let filter_settings be dictionary containing
        Set filter_settings["type"] to filter_type_to_number with type as template_voice["filter"]["type"]
        Set filter_settings["cutoff"] to template_voice["filter"]["cutoff_frequency"]
        Set filter_settings["resonance"] to template_voice["filter"]["resonance"]
        Set filter_settings["envelope_amount"] to template_voice["filter"]["envelope_amount"]
        Set preset["filter_settings"] to filter_settings
    
    Note: Save global settings
    Set preset["global_settings"]["master_volume"] to synth["master_volume"]
    Set preset["global_settings"]["pitch_bend_range"] to synth["pitch_bend_range"]
    
    Return preset

Process called "load_synth_preset" that takes synth as Synthesizer and preset as SynthPreset returns Synthesizer:
    Note: Apply global settings
    If preset["global_settings"] contains "master_volume":
        Set synth["master_volume"] to preset["global_settings"]["master_volume"]
    If preset["global_settings"] contains "pitch_bend_range":
        Set synth["pitch_bend_range"] to preset["global_settings"]["pitch_bend_range"]
    
    Note: Apply settings to all voices
    For each voice in synth["voices"]:
        Note: Apply oscillator settings
        For i from 0 to minimum of length of voice["oscillators"] and length of preset["oscillator_settings"] minus 1:
            Let osc_settings be preset["oscillator_settings"] at index i
            Let oscillator be voice["oscillators"] at index i
            
            If osc_settings contains "type":
                Set oscillator["type"] to number_to_oscillator_type with number as osc_settings["type"]
            If osc_settings contains "amplitude":
                Set oscillator["amplitude"] to osc_settings["amplitude"]
        
        Note: Apply filter settings
        If preset["filter_settings"] contains "cutoff":
            Set voice["filter"]["cutoff_frequency"] to preset["filter_settings"]["cutoff"]
        If preset["filter_settings"] contains "resonance":
            Set voice["filter"]["resonance"] to preset["filter_settings"]["resonance"]
    
    Return synth

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "midi_to_frequency" that takes note as Integer returns Float:
    Note: A4 (MIDI note 69) = 440 Hz
    Let semitones_from_a4 be note minus 69
    Return 440.0 times power of 2.0 and semitones_from_a4 divided by 12.0

Process called "clamp_sample" that takes sample as Float returns Float:
    Return maximum of negative 1.0 and minimum of 1.0 and sample

Process called "generate_voice_id" returns Integer:
    Note: Generate unique voice ID using system UUID generation
    Try:
        Return system_call_generate_unique_id
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to timestamp-based ID generation
        Let timestamp be system_call_get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
        Let random_component be system_call_get_secure_random_integer
        Return (timestamp modulo 1000000) plus (random_component modulo 65536)

Process called "oscillator_type_to_number" that takes type as OscillatorType returns Float:
    Match type:
        When SINE:
            Return 0.0
        When TRIANGLE:
            Return 1.0
        When SQUARE:
            Return 2.0
        When SAW:
            Return 3.0
        When NOISE:
            Return 4.0
        When WAVETABLE:
            Return 5.0
        Otherwise:
            Return 0.0

Process called "number_to_oscillator_type" that takes number as Float returns OscillatorType:
    Let int_number be integer from number
    Match int_number:
        When 0:
            Return SINE
        When 1:
            Return TRIANGLE
        When 2:
            Return SQUARE
        When 3:
            Return SAW
        When 4:
            Return NOISE
        When 5:
            Return WAVETABLE
        Otherwise:
            Return SINE

Process called "filter_type_to_number" that takes type as FilterType returns Float:
    Match type:
        When LOW_PASS_24DB:
            Return 0.0
        When HIGH_PASS_24DB:
            Return 1.0
        When BAND_PASS_12DB:
            Return 2.0
        Otherwise:
            Return 0.0

Note: Mathematical Helper Functions
Let PI be 3.141592653589793
Let TWO_PI be 6.283185307179586

Process called "sine" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Taylor series approximation for sine
    Let result be x
    Let term be x
    For i from 1 to 10:
        Set term to negative term times x times x divided by ((2 times i) times (2 times i plus 1))
        Set result to result plus term
    Return result

Process called "cosine" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: cos(x) = sin(x + π/2)
    Return sine of (x plus PI divided by 2.0)

Process called "power" that takes base as Float and exponent as Float returns Float:
    Note: e^(exponent * ln(base))
    Return exponential of (exponent times natural_log of base)

Process called "exponential" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Taylor series for e^x
    Let result be 1.0
    Let term be 1.0
    For i from 1 to 20:
        Set term to term times x divided by i
        Set result to result plus term
    Return result

Process called "natural_log" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Natural logarithm using series expansion
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return negative 1000.0
    If x is equal to 1.0:
        Return 0.0
    
    Let y be (x minus 1.0) divided by (x plus 1.0)
    Let y_squared be y times y
    Let result be y
    Let term be y
    
    For i from 1 to 20:
        Set term to term times y_squared
        Set result to result plus term divided by (2 times i plus 1)
    
    Return 2.0 times result

Process called "square_root" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Newton's method for square root
    If x is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    If x is equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    Let guess be x divided by 2.0
    For i from 1 to 10:
        Set guess to (guess plus x divided by guess) divided by 2.0
    Return guess

Process called "maximum" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    If a is greater than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Process called "minimum" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    If a is less than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Process called "minimum" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is less than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Process called "integer" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Convert float to integer (truncate)
    If value is greater than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0  Note: Simplified - would do proper conversion
    Otherwise:
        Return 0

Note: System Interface Functions
Process called "system_random" returns Integer:
    Note: System random number generator using cryptographically secure source
    Try:
        Return system_call_get_secure_random_integer
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to timestamp-based entropy
        Let timestamp be system_call_get_current_timestamp_nanoseconds
        Return (timestamp times 1664525 plus 1013904223) modulo 2147483647

Process called "get_current_time_ms" returns Float:
    Note: Get current time in milliseconds with high precision
    Try:
        Return system_call_get_current_timestamp_milliseconds as Float
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to system clock if high-precision call fails
        Let seconds be system_call_get_current_timestamp_seconds
        Return seconds times 1000.0

Note: Additional audio processing helper functions
Process called "get_grain_sample" that takes oscillator as Oscillator and phase as Float returns Float:
    Note: Sample from audio buffer or generate from oscillator for granular synthesis
    Try:
        If oscillator contains "audio_buffer":
            Let buffer_index be integer from (phase modulo length of oscillator["audio_buffer"]["samples"])
            Return oscillator["audio_buffer"]["samples"] at index buffer_index
        Otherwise:
            Return sine_wave with phase as phase
    
    Catch error:
        Return sine_wave with phase as phase

Process called "clamp_audio" that takes sample as Float returns Float:
    Note: Clamp audio sample to valid range [-1.0, 1.0]
    Return maximum of -1.0 and minimum of 1.0 and sample

Process called "clamp_range" that takes value as Float and min_val as Float and max_val as Float returns Float:
    Note: Clamp value to specified range
    Return maximum of min_val and minimum of max_val and value

Note: Audio Buffer Functions (imported from other modules)
Process called "create_audio_buffer" that takes channels as Integer and sample_rate as Float and length as Integer returns AudioBuffer:
    Let samples be list containing
    For i from 0 to channels times length minus 1:
        Add 0.0 to samples
    Return AudioBuffer with:
        samples as samples
        channels as channels
        sample_rate as sample_rate
        length as length
        metadata as dictionary containing

Type called "AudioBuffer":
    samples as List[Float]
    channels as Integer
    sample_rate as Float
    length as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "AudioEffect":
    name as String
    parameters as Dictionary[String, Float]
    enabled as Boolean
    bypass as Boolean